00:17:37,500 --> 00:17:41,361
Do the thing, and people will eventually recognize you for it.

325
00:17:41,361 --> 00:17:44,502
I also learned the publishing process, which I'm not going to read this whole thing, because

326
00:17:44,502 --> 00:17:46,182
I only have a few minutes left.

327
00:17:46,182 --> 00:17:46,422
But...

328
00:17:48,375 --> 00:17:52,837
In summary, you submit your idea to an editor who's in charge of finding new books.

329
00:17:52,837 --> 00:17:55,477
They're called acquisitions editors.

330
00:17:55,477 --> 00:18:00,678
Then you work with them to develop an outline that provides something different from what's

331
00:18:00,678 --> 00:18:01,939
already on the market.

332
00:18:01,939 --> 00:18:05,060
So again, that goes back to the idea of filling in knowledge gaps.

333
00:18:05,060 --> 00:18:08,060
If you are contributing something that's never been contributed before,

334
00:18:08,340 --> 00:18:10,181
the publisher will get really excited.

335
00:18:10,181 --> 00:18:15,183
So then once you've established this and usually gone through a round of peer review,

336
00:18:15,183 --> 00:18:21,525
so submitting to people in the industry that look at your proposal and say, yeah, that's

337
00:18:21,525 --> 00:18:22,866
a thing that should exist.

338
00:18:23,686 --> 00:18:28,292
You write your manuscript, give it to the editors, and they help you arrange your content,

339
00:18:28,292 --> 00:18:33,519
check it for grammar, make it sound better than it did when it just came out of your

340
00:18:33,519 --> 00:18:37,605
fingers when you were perhaps a little too tired to type.

341
00:18:37,605 --> 00:18:41,050
But it's put into a final layout, printed, and then book.

342
00:18:42,455 --> 00:18:47,439
I also learned how to best choose the release method for content.

343
00:18:47,439 --> 00:18:53,843
I'm talking a lot about books and publishing, but I've talked with a lot of people that

344
00:18:53,843 --> 00:18:57,365
have said, no, I want my stuff to be available for free.

345
00:18:57,365 --> 00:19:03,809
I go with what I go with because as an academic, I get credit in my day job for publishing

346
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:05,410
with presses.

347
00:19:05,410 --> 00:19:07,451
That's just part of the academic thing.

348
00:19:08,992 --> 00:19:13,195
if you are weighing which one to go with.

349
00:19:13,195 --> 00:19:14,015
Here's a breakdown.

350
00:19:14,015 --> 00:19:16,677
Publishers are great.

351
00:19:16,677 --> 00:19:19,239
They do a lot of things for you, but your work

352
00:19:19,239 --> 00:19:20,800
becomes part of their business model.

353
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:21,660
They sell it.

354
00:19:21,660 --> 00:19:23,682
They may even own your manuscript.

355
00:19:23,682 --> 00:19:27,464
I've had friends who want to get their manuscript republished,

356
00:19:27,464 --> 00:19:28,845
but the publisher doesn't want to do it,

357
00:19:28,845 --> 00:19:30,926
so they had to buy their manuscript back.

358
00:19:30,926 --> 00:19:33,288
So be aware of that.

359
00:19:33,288 --> 00:19:37,911
It's really not that big a deal day to day, but be aware of it.

360
00:19:38,870 --> 00:19:43,534
Putting it out on the internet for free lets you reach lots of people, regardless of their

361
00:19:43,534 --> 00:19:48,197
ability to pay for content, and that's really important.

362
00:19:48,197 --> 00:19:53,081
Diversity and economic diversity is really important, and I really respect the people

363
00:19:53,081 --> 00:19:58,125
who do choose to put stuff out for free to help.

364
00:19:58,945 --> 00:20:01,869
people, to help content reach people.

365
00:20:01,869 --> 00:20:08,336
The downside of this, though, is that it lacks a system of checks and balances to help every

366
00:20:08,336 --> 00:20:13,902
bit of proving that you are the person who should be talking about this, to editing your

367
00:20:13,902 --> 00:20:17,726
content, making it sound good.

368
00:20:17,967 --> 00:20:19,747
something you have to take on your own,

369
00:20:19,747 --> 00:20:21,488
and you also have to do your own marketing.

370
00:20:21,488 --> 00:20:23,268
Publishers do marketing for you.

371
00:20:23,268 --> 00:20:25,669
So both have their ups and downs,

372
00:20:25,669 --> 00:20:26,889
and those are things to think about.

373
00:20:26,889 --> 00:20:30,750
And then lastly, and another important thing,

374
00:20:30,750 --> 00:20:32,791
is making a famous game is not the only way

